text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts]]%0a%0a!Tone system comparing English and Somali%0a%0a:Author: sgangu%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aEnglish has no tones while Somali has simple tones %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aTone is similar to musical pitch. However, languages can use tone while speaking without being a tonal language. Even in standard American English, we sometimes raise our voice at the end of a sentence to indicate that it's a question. However, this upspeak does not change the words' actual meaning. However, in a tonal language like Chinese, the same vowels and consonants can be pronounced with different tone to take on a different meaning. For example, the word "ma" can be pronounced with different tones to mean either "horse", "hemp", "scold", or "mom". %0aSome languages have more tones than others to signify meaning. Some pitch-accent languages only have 2 tones to convey meaning. One interesting fact is that places that are more humid have developed more tonal languages because humid air allows for more movement of vocal cords. %0a%0aIn English, no matter the tone we use when we are speaking, the meaning of the word remains the same. Somali, on the other hand, has a simple tone system. The three basic tones are high, low, and falling. In this language, tone is strongly coupled with stress and it also works on a grammatical level. The vowels and consonants in boy and girl in Somali are the same but the stress and the tone in the two words is what differentiates them. %0a%0aIt would be interesting to study how difficult native English speakers find it to pronounce words in Somali (or other tonal languages). I imagine it would be much more difficult than trying to pronounce words that do not have tonal differences. This also leads me to wonder if non-tonal languages are capable of evolving to take on tonal qualities, or if language is not capable of taking on a whole new feature but only new words. %0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.babbel.com/en/magazine/tonal-languages%0ahttps://www.mustgo.com/worldlanguages/somali/#:~:text=The%2520tonal%2520system%2520of%2520Somali,in%2520languages%2520such%2520as%2520Chinese.%0ahttps://phoible.org/inventories/view/127%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)
