diff:1613883444:1613883444:=1,78d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Tone system comparing English and Somali%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: sgangu%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c English has no tones while Somali has simple tones %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Tone is similar to musical pitch. However, languages can use tone while speaking without being a tonal language. Even in standard American English, we sometimes raise our voice at the end of a sentence to indicate that it's a question. However, this upspeak does not change the words' actual meaning. However, in a tonal language like Chinese, the same vowels and consonants can be pronounced with different tone to take on a different meaning. For example, the word "ma" can be pronounced with different tones to mean either "horse", "hemp", "scold", or "mom". %0a%3c Some languages have more tones than others to signify meaning. Some pitch-accent languages only have 2 tones to convey meaning. One interesting fact is that places that are more humid have developed more tonal languages because humid air allows for more movement of vocal cords. %0a%3c %0a%3c In English, no matter the tone we use when we are speaking, the meaning of the word remains the same. Somali, on the other hand, has a simple tone system. The three basic tones are high, low, and falling. In this language, tone is strongly coupled with stress and it also works on a grammatical level. The vowels and consonants in boy and girl in Somali are the same but the stress and the tone in the two words is what differentiates them. %0a%3c %0a%3c It would be interesting to study how difficult native English speakers find it to pronounce words in Somali (or other tonal languages). I imagine it would be much more difficult than trying to pronounce words that do not have tonal differences. This also leads me to wonder if non-tonal languages are capable of evolving to take on tonal qualities, or if language is not capable of taking on a whole new feature but only new words. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.babbel.com/en/magazine/tonal-languages%0a%3c https://www.mustgo.com/worldlanguages/somali/#:~:text=The%2520tonal%2520system%2520of%2520Somali,in%2520languages%2520such%2520as%2520Chinese.%0a%3c https://phoible.org/inventories/view/127%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: :)%0a%3c (:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
